{
  "text": "Intriguingly, spatial QRS-T angle was found to be by far the strongest marker when compared to other classical CV risk factors and traditional ECG risk indicators such as left ventricular hypertrophy, left bundle branch block, T-wave inversion and QTc interval [CITATION_1] . In National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey III participants without clinically evident CVD at the start of the study, abnormal spatial QRS-T angle (136\u00b0 for men 121\u00b0 for women) was associated with a doubling of the risk for CV death including suspected SCD [CITATION_2] . Frontal QRS-T angle was also shown to be predictive of CV outcomes. In a large study involving the Finnish general population, high frontal QRS-T angle (>100\u00b0) conferred a threefold increased risk of SCD over a 30-year follow up period [CITATION_3] . Notably, in a previous analysis in the MESA cohort, adults free of CVD at baseline but with extreme frontal QRS-T angle (95th percentile) at baseline (MESA visit 1) had a higher incidence of composite outcomes of CVD [CITATION_4] . In addition to general population studies, there have been numerous studies linking QRS-T angle to adverse CVD outcomes in patients with known CVD.",
